column2:
@Jamie_ethnft @adamhunt__ @wallamolla @matthewegould @unstoppableweb @ensdomains Would you like me to retract my previous statement so you don't get too caught up in focusing on this one specific detail?

I'll reword it for you, ok?

ENS has positioned themselves into the highest probability of obtaining the .eth DNS extension for the reasons stated above

@adamhunt__ @wallamolla @Jamie_ethnft @matthewegould @unstoppableweb @ensdomains Let's say, hypothetically just as a thought experiment, that UD decided to use their framework &amp; issue their own .eth TLD on behalf of UD's name

Who would then be officially recognized as the real .eth?

Being recognized as the standard is very important else you convolute all

@adamhunt__ @wallamolla @Jamie_ethnft @matthewegould @unstoppableweb @ensdomains It's hard to fit all of that into one tweet, I apologize

The idea is simple: ENS is standing by .eth and only .eth for the foreseeable future as a staple of their protocol

The official DNS TLD is unused and so this gives ENS the highest likelihood of obtaining the eth extension

@Jamie_ethnft @matthewegould @unstoppableweb @ensdomains lol only ENS has issues and not UD? If that's the argument maybe we shouldn't be having this discussion

Renewal fees aren't a bug, it's a feature that ensures the sustainability of the protocol

Imagine if DNS domains never expired and premiums were locked forever lmao

@Jamie_ethnft @matthewegould @unstoppableweb @ensdomains To be fair I don't believe you should be buying "premium" UD names even if you could afford it

They're static NFTs not backed by anything and the more TLDs they issue the more likely they are to have their names compromised should DNS decide to issue them

$100k UD premiums lmao

@Jamie_ethnft @matthewegould @unstoppableweb @ensdomains You can apply that argument to virtually anything if you try hard enough and at this point I'm not sure it warrants a response

It's not my job to convince you, the market is doing a fantastic job of speaking on my behalf

Best of luck fren

@Jamie_ethnft @matthewegould @unstoppableweb @ensdomains I hope you haven't invested too much money into UD NFTs fren

You can keep trying to throw some gotchas my way but.. please point me to the direction of any recent large sales that compare even the slightest to ENS and I would greatly appreciate it

It's a protocol, not a company

@Jamie_ethnft @matthewegould @unstoppableweb @ensdomains Ethiopia is the current placeholder of the TLD .eth there is no doubt about it

However, the extension largely goes unused for various reasons &amp; ENS is largely recognized and issuing no other TLD's

The math is pretty simple to workout when you have industry leaders pushing ENS

@Jamie_ethnft @matthewegould @unstoppableweb @ensdomains All I can do is direct you to the word of the DAO - that's what it means to have a truly decentralized protocol, there is no one individual running the show

Domains need to expire if you want there to be any semblance of a naming protocol to have any longevity

I promise you

@DomainIncite @Jamie_ethnft @matthewegould @unstoppableweb @ensdomains Do you believe that the global naming space should be fractionalized? I sure don't and I don't believe you should either

Why do you think ENS hasn't issued more TLD's than .eth the way so many other naming "companies" have?

DNS isn't going away - some food for thought

@Jamie_ethnft @matthewegould @unstoppableweb @ensdomains Sorry I'm not understanding what you are trying to say here

So your complaint isn't with ENS itself, but the very decentralized model in which it and everything else is built upon to begin with? 

You might have to get in touch with the Bitcoin CEO about that one

@Jamie_ethnft @matthewegould @unstoppableweb @ensdomains You seem to be making comparisons in a quite whimsical manner

How is ENS not innovating? More so, what steps is UD taking in your opinion to separate itself from the crowd?

At least it's well understood that ENS is the king, glad we can agree on that

@Jamie_ethnft @matthewegould @unstoppableweb @ensdomains The distinction is pretty easily understood

UD is a centralized entity that sells domains they themselves have minted for a premium - it's their business model

ENS is a protocol that needs verly little human intervention to continue operating smoothly long into the future

@Jamie_ethnft @matthewegould @unstoppableweb @ensdomains Who is the "I" in letting you keep it? It's a decentralized smart contract

If you trust the nature of virtually any popularized smart contract you should have no problem trusting ENS as the code has been properly and thoroughly audited

UD is just another NFT; not a protocol

@Jamie_ethnft @matthewegould @unstoppableweb @ensdomains Couldn't agree more with this point

Web3 won't just be Ethereum based, but that's largely what it is referred to at the moment

Did you know that ENS is effectively a decentralized phonebook? You can update your text-records to point to anything you want on an immutable ledger

@Jamie_ethnft @matthewegould @unstoppableweb @ensdomains Thanks for taking the time to reply

Curious what you mean by UD having a better future in web space? If you weren't aware, ENS is recognized by ICANN whereas UD to my knowledge is not

In the future if an extension like .crypto or .nft is adopted by DNS.. what then?

Do you love @ensdomains but find third-party markets such as OpenSea difficult to work with?

@kodexapp is an #ENS dedicated marketplace with all sorts of cool features - and it's launching very soon üöÄüöÄüöÄ

https://t.co/BdxdqbNX9u

@ptonerdoteth Or I could just send funds to ptoner.eth instead of first identifying the mooncat not only by visual appearance but by unique identifier

All of the necessary info is there to send funds to ptoner.eth

Why add another layer?
